<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-641-488  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 641 488.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  August 17 1989 v15 n17 p37(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Alberta researchers speed network recovery. (Research atEdmonton's Alberta Telecommunication Research Centre)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Adhikari, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at the Alberta Telecommunication Research Centre inEdmonton develop Selfhealing, a network management softwarecapable of restoring communications traffic within two secondsafter a cable cutting incident.andP;  Selfhealing works on anintelligent network node technology that speeds the recoveryprocess by bypassing the failure rather than relying upon acentral data base.andP;  Telecom Canada is planning to evaluate thesoftware on the electronic digital crossconnect systems (DCS) itemploys to route communications traffic.andP;  The effect of thetechnology is to turn the entire transport network into a singledistributed multi-processor.andP;  Tests are being conducted onsimulations of Telecom Canada's entire fiber optic and microwavenetwork.andP;  Licensing negotiations with several US manufacturers arealso taking place.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Telecom Canada (innovations).andO;Topic:     Alberta Telecommunication Research CentreResearch and DevelopmentNetwork Management SoftwareFiber OpticsVandalismDistributed Processing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>